  "enhanced_information": "In this scenario, the boy diagnosed with uncomplicated pulmonary tuberculosis is on isoniazid, rifampin, and ethambutol. It is well-established that close contacts of individuals with active tuberculosis, especially young children, should receive isoniazid prophylaxis to prevent infection. Therefore, his 3-year-old sibling should indeed receive INH prophylaxis. Regarding auditory function, while ethambutol can cause optic neuritis, it does not primarily affect auditory function, making a baseline auditory function test unnecessary before treatment. Polyarthralgia is not a common adverse effect associated with isoniazid or rifampin, although it can occur with some medications; thus, this statement is misleading. Lastly, if the mother is not infected with tuberculosis, she does not require INH prophylaxis. Therefore, the most accurate statement is that the 3-year-old sibling should receive INH prophylaxis."
